\begin_layout Title
Camera Trap Study on Farm Woltemade, Namibia: Perception vs reality - Did
 a reported increase in leopard numbers coincide with a decrease in cheetah
 numbers?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Chavoux Luyt
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Interaction between predators is an important ecological aspect of their
 spatial and temporal behaviour with implications for human-wildlife conflict
 and predator conservation.
 These include aspects like meso-predator release in the absence of top
 predators, behavioural changes in the presence of other predators, and
 habitat niche contraction in the presence of other predators (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Bartnick_et_al_2013"

\end_inset

).
 This study aims to see if the reported increase in leopard numbers and
 coincidental decrease in cheetah numbers actually corresponds with the
 data and if intra-guild competition could cause a decrease in cheetah numbers
 on Namibian farmlands.
 For this purpose, it uses historical camera trap data and compares it to
 a new camera trap survey in the same season and at the same sites as the
 previous study.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Introduction 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Interaction between predators, be it direct competition, lethal confrontations,
 spatial and temporal avoidance of other predators 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Durant_2000,Hayward_n_Slotow_2009,Bartnick_et_al_2013"

\end_inset

 or meso-predator release when top predators are removed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ritchie_and_Johnson_2009"

\end_inset

, is an important ecological aspect of predator behaviour that can impact
 farmer-predator conflict.
 For cheetahs (
\shape italic
Acinonyx jubatus
\shape default
), competition with larger predators is one of the main reasons why conserved
 areas alone are considered insufficient to ensure their long-term survival
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Mills_n_Mills_2014"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
A number of Namibian farmers have reported an increase in leopard numbers
 and a simultaneous decrease in cheetah numbers (pers.
 comm.
 Francois Kok, Rolf Ritter and others).
 The reported increase in leopards could be causing a decline in cheetah
 as the result of direct lethal confrontation between leopards and cheetahs,
 cheetahs avoiding areas with high leopard density ("fear and loathing"
 sensu 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Ritchie_and_Johnson_2009"

\end_inset

), habitat changes more favourable to leopards, changes in available prey
 species, a disproportionate number of cheetahs killed by farmers compared
 to leopards, or other currently unknown reasons.
 However, no such change has been reported on the land of the Cheetah Conservati
on Fund (CCF), where no predators are killed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Woltemade Guest and Hunting Farm is situated in North Central Namibia, about
 40km Northwest of Hochfeld (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:Map-of-study"

\end_inset

).
 It is a guest and hunting farm as well as a working cattle farm of about
 22 000 ha with its own butchery in total and forms part of the Sandveld
 conservancy.
 The farm falls within the Thornbush shrubland vegetation type of Namibia,
 growing on chromic Cambisols in the southern part, petric Calcisols in
 the centre and ferric Arenosols soil types in the northern part of the
 farm.
 In 2008 CCF did a three month camera trap survey on the land as part of
 a larger project to determine cheetah densities on Namibian farmlands.
 A total of 3890 pictures were taken, of which 19% where cheetahs, allowing
 for the identification of six different cheetahs 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Marker_2008"

\end_inset

.
 Other predators, including leopard, were also recorded but not identified
 or counted.
 Two cameras were used per site and cameras were placed at 10 play trees
 and next to one road.
 This was done as part of a larger cheetah survey to estimate the mean density
 (and total numbers) of cheetahs in North Central Namibia 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Marker_2005"

\end_inset

.
 This historical data present us with an opportunity to test whether the
 perceived increase in leopard numbers really coincided with a decrease
 in cheetah numbers.
\end_layout

