\begin_layout Section*
Aims and objectives 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
The main aim of the camera trap study is to determine if there has really
 been an increase in leopard numbers on the farm Woltemade and secondly,
 if such an increase coincided with a decrease in cheetah numbers.
 If a simultaneous but opposite change in numbers has indeed occurred, more
 research into the reasons for this change needs to be done.
 Any circumstantial data that can shed light on possible reasons for a change
 in the relative predator numbers, will also be collected.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Methods & materials
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Because this will basically be a repeat of the previous camera trap survey,
 the field methods will correspond as far as possible with the methods used
 in 2008.
 In March 2014, 22 camera traps will be set at the exact same 11 sites and
 in the same season of the year as the previous survey.
 In order to keep the protocol the same as the previous study, the camera
 timer will be set to take 3 pictures at 30 second intervals when movement
 is detected in front of the camera.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Camera trap surveys as a method to estimate abundance and density have some
 advantages compared to other methods which influenced the original decision
 on the methods used 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Marker_2005"

\end_inset

.
 It is non-invasive, much cheaper than GPS collars while also giving better
 density estimates and being less labour intensive than spoor tracking 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Balme_et_al_2009"

\end_inset

.
 In contrast to hair traps and scat dogs, it also does not require expensive
 DNA analysis in order to identify individuals 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Long_et_al_2007b"

\end_inset

, but can use identifying marks (spots or stripes) to identify individuals
 for density estimates using capture-recapture models (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "OConnell_et_al_2011,Marnewick_et_al_2008,Royle_et_al_2009,Chapman_n_Balme_2010,Borchers_2012,Foster_n_Harmsen_2012,Rovero_et_al_2013"

\end_inset

, but see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Carbone_et_al_2001,Rowcliffe_et_al_2008"

\end_inset

 for examples of using camera traps for estimating population densities
 without identifying individuals).
\end_layout

