\begin_layout Section*
Conclusion 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Although the camera trap study will not be able to prove that there has
 been a general increase in leopard numbers (and simultaneous decrease in
 cheetah numbers) in Northern Namibia, it should be able to test if this
 effect as reported by one farmer, is real or not.
 Even if this data can not be extrapolated to the whole of North Central
 Namibia, it can provide supportive evidence that the reported change in
 predator composition on these farmlands are real.
 If there is a real effect, it will imply that more research is needed on
 the causes of the change in predator numbers.
 Any additional data on rainfall, vegetation changes, game and livestock
 numbers and management can also be provided as possible causes for the
 change in predator numbers that needs to be investigated.
 Spoor tracking will later (from July 2014 onward) be used to provide more
 detail on the spatial behaviour of the four predator species that can have
 an economic impact on livestock farming in Northern Namibia.
 There are a number of different possible outcomes to the project, each
 with its own implications:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
It is possible that there has been no significant change in either leopard
 or cheetah numbers.
 The perceived change that was reported might be simply because of an increase
 in livestock losses from leopard depredation, leading to farmers thinking
 that there has been an increase in leopard numbers.
 Increasing livestock losses from leopards might be caused by them switching
 to livestock as prey because of changes in wild prey availability, changes
 in farm management bringing more vulnerable livestock into contact with
 areas of high leopard density, or any number of other reasons that does
 not entail an increase in numbers.
 Because of the rise of conservancies, it is also possible that predators
 are less persecuted than before, changing their behaviour, and so they
 are simply seen more easily by farmers.
 Of course, since this study can only be done on the one farm for which
 historical data are available, it is also possible that the sample sizes
 might be too small to show significance, even if there was a real change
 in numbers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There might be an actual increase in leopard numbers, but no change in cheetah
 numbers.
 This will indicate that a number of possible reasons could cause an increase
 in leopard numbers, but that these factors don’t really influence the numbers
 of cheetahs and also that leopards are unlikely to influence cheetah numbers
 through direct competition or outright killing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There might actually be an increase in the numbers of leopards and a simultaneou
s decrease in the numbers of cheetahs as reported by farmers.
 This will not indicate any reason for the changes in numbers, it would
 suggest that is possible that leopards can have a direct effect on the
 numbers of cheetahs and that the interaction between these two species
 should be investigated further (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Mills_n_Mills_2014"

\end_inset

 provides an example of leopard predation on cheetah cubs).
 The reason for such changes will be important, both to ensure the long-term
 survival of the cheetah and for farmers to adapt their management practices
 to take into account the difference in behaviour and predation risk between
 leopards and cheetahs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There might be an increase in both leopard and cheetah numbers.
 This will indicate that circumstances have somehow changed (e.g.
 a change in habitat, number of available prey species or management changes)
 so that both predator species benefit.
 It might mean that farmers should consider additional management practices
 to protect their livestock from both predator species.
 It can also be seen as an indication that the current management of Woltemade
 farm and neighbouring conservancy members are benefiting predator conservation,
 although other factors like weather, habitat or prey changes might be more
 important.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
It is also possible that farmers are mistaken and there has actually been
 an increase in cheetah numbers, while leopard numbers decreased or stayed
 the same.
 If true, more research will be required to find the reason for such a change.
\end_layout

